.SH NAME
FileSystemFileEntry.file \- FileSystemFileEntry: file() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[CR]FileSystemFileEntry\f[R] interface\[cq]s method
\f[B]\f[CB]file()\f[B]\f[R] returns a \f[CR]File\f[R] object which can
be used to read data from the file represented by the directory entry.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
file(successCallback)
file(successCallback, errorCallback)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]successCallback\f[R]
A callback function which is called when the \f[CR]File\f[R] has been
created successfully; the \f[CR]File\f[R] is passed into the callback as
the only parameter.
.TP
\f[B]errorCallback\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
If provided, this must be a method which is called when an error occurs
while trying to create the \f[CR]File\f[R].
This callback receives as input a \f[CR]DOMException\f[R] object
describing the error.
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SH EXAMPLES
This example establishes a method, \f[CR]readFile()\f[R], reads a text
file and calls a specified callback function with the received text (in
a string) once the read is completed.
If an error occurs, a specified (optional) error callback is called.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]function\f[R] readFile(entry, successCallback, errorCallback) {
  entry.file((file) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    \f[B]let\f[R] reader = \f[B]new\f[R] FileReader();

    reader.onload = () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
      successCallback(reader.result);
    };

    reader.onerror = () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
      errorCallback(reader.error);
    };

    reader.readAsText(file);
  }, errorCallback);
}
.EE
.PP
This function calls \f[CR]file()\f[R], specifying as its success
callback a method which proceeds to use a \f[CR]FileReader\f[R] to read
the file as text.
The FileReader\[cq]s \f[CR]load\f[R] event handler is set up to deliver
the loaded string to the \f[CR]successCallback\f[R] specified when the
\f[CR]readFile()\f[R] method was called; similarly, its \f[CR]error\f[R]
handler is set up to call the \f[CR]errorCallback\f[R] specified.
